Machine learning is divided into three categories:
1-)SUPERVISED LEARNING
The goal of supervised learning is for the machine to learn from a large number of labeled examples.

APPLICATIONS:
Email spam filtering
Disease diagnosis
Credit scoring
Image classification

POPULAR ALGORITHMS:
Linear Regression
Logistic Regression
Decision Trees
Random Forest
Support Vector Machines (SVM)
Neural Networks

2-)UNSUPERVISED LEARNING
Unsupervised learning involves organizing data into different clusters or discovering different perspectives to simplify complex data and improve data analysis
EXAMPLE: Consider a machine learning system tasked with sorting a collection of wildlife photos that contain no information about animal species. In this example, unsupervised learning algorithms can identify similar features in the images and group them without being explicitly instructed about a specific animal.

APPLICATIONS:
Customer segmentation
Anomaly detection
Feature reduction (dimensionality reduction)
Image clustering

POPULAR ALGORITHMS:

K-Means Clustering
Hierarchical Clustering
DBSCAN
Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
Autoencoders

3-)REINFORCEMENT LEARNING
The algorithm processes input data to generate outputs and then receives an immediate feedback signal that measures the effectiveness of the output.

APPLICATIONS:
Artificial intelligence in gaming (e.g., AlphaGo)
Autonomous vehicles
Robot motion control
Portfolio optimization

POPULAR ALGORITHMS:
Translated with DeepL.com (free version)
Q-Learning
Deep Q-Networks (DQN)
Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO)
Policy Gradient Methods
SARSA
